                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d294">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/7761: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Earle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sofia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-01-21T16:00:00+02:00"
                            >January 21, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 21—3:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>27. After an interview with the Minister for Foreign Affairs and the Minister of
                    War, Colonel Donovan<note n="28" xml:id="d294fn28">William J. Donovan,
                        Unofficial Observer of the Secretary of the Navy of the United
                        States.</note> feels that the Bulgarian Government expects Germany to occupy
                    Bulgaria; that they are very unhappy about it but that they will not resist this
                    occupation. I concur in this opinion.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Earle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
